---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
// The headshot has not left the project — the footer still imports it, because
// it crops to a 52px square where a full-length shot would be a suit with no
// face in it. The hero is the only place that needed the full-length version.
import heroPortrait from '@/assets/portrait/ahmed-hamdy-hero.webp';
import formulaHome from '@/assets/formula4you/formula4you-platform-home.webp';
import { external, withBase } from '@config/site';
import Disclosure from '@/components/Disclosure.astro';

/**
 * CONTENT NOTE — why this reads the way it does.
 *
 * The previous copy described a method in the abstract: "I map how work moves",
 * "I review clarity and trust". True of every consultant alive, and therefore
 * evidence of nothing. Ahmed's verdict was correct — it read as generated.
 *
 * The rule applied here: every claim is either something he did, something he
 * decided, or something he refused. No adjective stacking. No parallel
 * three-bullet symmetry. Where the evidence stops, the copy says so.
 */


---

<div class="home">
  <section class="hero" aria-labelledby="home-title">
    <div class="wrap hero__grid">
      <div class="hero__copy reveal is-visible">
        <p class="eyebrow">Ahmed Hamdy · Business Operations &amp; Process Improvement Consultant</p>
        {/* Three beats, then the turn. The old headline — "Different teams see
            different problems, I connect the pattern" — was true of any
            consultant, which is why it read as generated. This one names three
            departments (the breadth) and lands on the insight that is actually
            his. */}
        <h1 id="home-title">It slows down sales. It shows up in support. <span>It started somewhere else.</span></h1>
        {/* The hero sheds its bio into the About section directly below it — the
            visitor gets the shape of the page first, then the substance. One
            line stays, because the headline earns a single answer. The old two
            paragraphs also framed the consulting by industry (telecom, steel,
            petroleum); that framing was wrong — the work is a discipline, not a
            sector — and it now lives, correctly, in the About. */}
        <p class="hero__lede">I find where a problem actually started, and fix the thing there — not the department it lands in.</p>
        {/* Said on the first screen, in one line, without the halo. A visitor
            who does not know it is free will not ask. A visitor who is told it
            is a favour will also not ask. */}
        <p class="hero__free"><span></span>First conversation is free — I learn as much from it as you do</p>
        <div class="cluster hero__actions">
          <a class="btn btn--primary" href="#diagnosis">See how I diagnose it <span class="btn__arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</span></a>
          <a class="btn" href="#evidence">See the platform I built <span class="btn__arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
        </div>

        {/* The index that used to live here — six numbered labels of the page —
            is now the page itself: the three case panels below are collapsed
            headers you can see the shape of on arrival, and the short sections
            follow them. Listing the parts in the hero as well was saying the
            same thing twice and made the hero tall for no reason. */}
      </div>

      <div class="system-lens" aria-label="Customer, support, sales and operations signals converging around Ahmed's portrait">
        <span class="lens-glow" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        {/* Deliberately small parallax throw. The figure bleeds past its cell to
            reach the hero's edges, so a large translate would drag a hard edge
            into view — the one thing the masks exist to prevent. */}
        <div class="hero-figure" data-parallax="-0.14">
          <Image src={heroPortrait} alt="Ahmed Hamdy" widths={[420, 640, 900, 1122]} sizes="(max-width: 900px) 82vw, 42vw" loading="eager" />
        </div>
        <span class="hero-figure__tag">Business signal → operating decision</span>
        <span class="orbit-node orbit-node--support" data-parallax="0.55">Support signal</span>
        <span class="orbit-node orbit-node--sales" data-parallax="-0.4">Sales friction</span>
        <span class="orbit-node orbit-node--ops" data-parallax="0.45">Operating constraint</span>
        <span class="orbit-node orbit-node--customer" data-parallax="-0.5">Customer behaviour</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* WHO I AM — the first real section, straight after the compact hero. Ahmed
      asked for a proper "about us" up front instead of a bio buried in the hero,
      and for the consulting to read as a discipline (growth, positioning, sales,
      customer-eye UX, team leadership, root-cause diagnosis) rather than a list
      of industries. The copy is his voice, drafted and adversarially judged: it
      leads on the one thing that is true of both halves of his record — he has
      run the function AND advised the founder, not only talked about either. */}
  <section class="who zone-paper" id="about">
    <div class="wrap who__grid">
      <div class="who__lead reveal">
        <span class="eyebrow">Who I am</span>
        <h2>Bring me something that is not working, and I will tell you where it actually started.</h2>
        <p>That is most of what I do, and it is the same move whether the thing in front of me is a support queue, a launch that stalled, a sales number that stopped moving, or a checkout people quietly abandon. Businesses are usually very good at describing the symptom and very bad at locating the cause — and the two are almost never in the same department.</p>
        <p>I start at the raw material rather than the summary: the actual conversations, the actual cancelled orders, the actual page somebody gave up on. By the time a problem reaches a meeting it has been summarised twice, and the detail that would have told you where it began is the first thing summarising removes.</p>
        <p>Since 2022 people have brought me whatever was wrong — how to grow profit without simply buying the growth, where they are genuinely different from the competitor beside them, why a team is not performing, whether a site loses the order long before the checkout. I am blunt about the answers: a lower price is not a strategy, more agents is not a fix, and sometimes the honest answer is that nothing should be built at all.</p>
        <p>None of that came from books. I spent almost two years inside a UK fintech's support function, promoted from the frontline to leading the team, where every failure in the business eventually arrived at my desk as somebody's complaint. Before that, and still, eight years of freelance customer support — thousands of conversations is the only way I know to learn what people actually ask and why. I run my own platform, Formula4You, where the operating decisions are mine and I am the one who lives with them. And I have worked from the outside of other people's businesses, from early-stage founders to large organisations, where judgement is the only thing I bring in the door.</p>
        <p class="who__close">Whatever is breaking, I run the same move on it: find where it actually started, name who owns it, and change the smallest thing that fixes it.</p>
      </div>

      <aside class="who__strengths reveal reveal-delay-1" aria-label="What I am good at">
        <span class="who__k">What I am good at</span>
        <ul>
          <li>I find where a problem actually lives — usually a process nobody owns, or a handoff nobody thought was theirs — instead of treating the place it surfaces.</li>
          <li>I lead a team from having done its work — I was promoted into running one from the frontline, not placed above it.</li>
          <li>I tell founders how to grow on relevance rather than price, and where they are genuinely different from whoever is beside them.</li>
          <li>I review a sales or e-commerce site as the customer buying from it, and point to the exact step where the order is lost.</li>
          <li>I say when nothing should be built — usually the least popular answer in the room, and often the correct one.</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* The forward-looking half. Everything above it is evidence of what he has
      done; this is the argument for why it is worth doing, and it is aimed at
      the founder who has not hit the wall yet. Stated as judgement, because
      that is what it is — attaching a proof point to every sentence of a
      professional view is what made the earlier drafts read defensive. */}
  <section class="early zone-night">
    <div class="wrap early__grid">
      <div class="early__head reveal">
        <span class="eyebrow">Where I am most useful</span>
        <h2>The problems that cost a large company a fortune were an afternoon's work when it was twelve people.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="early__body reveal reveal-delay-1">
        <p>Almost every expensive operational failure begins as a small, sensible decision taken early by someone who had no time to think about it. A category invented in a hurry. A status that meant one thing to the person who named it and something else to everyone who came after. A handoff that worked perfectly while the whole company sat in one room.</p>
        <p>None of that is a problem at twelve people. All of it is a problem at two hundred — and by then the fix is not a conversation. It is a migration, a retraining, a quarter of somebody's roadmap, and a year of reports that were quietly pointing at the wrong department.</p>
        <p>So the most valuable work I do is early: not building more, but deciding what should exist, who owns it, and what each word in your system will still mean when a hundred people are using it. Settling that in month three is close to free. Settling it in year three is a project.</p>
        <p>And if you are already large and it already hurts — that is most of what I do, and it is still worth doing. It simply costs more than it would have.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="early__pull reveal reveal-delay-2">Seeing the problem you are going to have is the cheapest work available to a business. Everything after it is repair.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* The cases are three organisations, which made the page read as "these
      three places are my whole career". They are examples of one method, and
      most of the work they illustrate belongs to clients and stays with them.
      Saying that out loud costs nothing and is true. */}
  <section class="examples zone-paper">
    <div class="wrap examples__row">
      <span class="eyebrow">Worked examples</span>
      <p>Three I can walk through end to end. Most of what I have done belongs to other people and stays with them — these are the ones I am free to show in detail. Open whichever is closest to your problem.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <details class="case" id="diagnosis" data-case>
    <summary class="case__head">
      <span class="case__n">Case 01</span>
      <span class="case__titles">
        <span class="case__t">A question that would not stop being asked.</span>
        <span class="case__ctx">Alpha Capital Group · UK fintech · support operations</span>
      </span>
      <span class="case__open">Read the case</span>
      <span class="case__chev" aria-hidden="true"><svg viewBox="0 0 16 10" width="16" height="10"><path d="M1 1l7 7 7-7" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" /></svg></span>
    </summary>
    <div class="case__body">
  <div class="journey">
    <svg class="journey__spine" viewBox="0 0 1440 2680" preserveAspectRatio="none" aria-hidden="true">
      <defs>
        <linearGradient id="journey-gradient" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
          <stop stop-color="#48e0bb" />
          <stop offset=".34" stop-color="#ff7a61" />
          <stop offset=".68" stop-color="#79b7ff" />
          <stop offset="1" stop-color="#48e0bb" />
        </linearGradient>
      </defs>
      <path class="journey__glow" d="M735 0C720 185 1040 230 930 470C820 700 455 615 510 900C558 1140 1015 1040 960 1320C902 1610 445 1500 520 1810C582 2070 970 1980 814 2680" />
      <path class="journey__line" d="M735 0C720 185 1040 230 930 470C820 700 455 615 510 900C558 1140 1015 1040 960 1320C902 1610 445 1500 520 1810C582 2070 970 1980 814 2680" />
      <circle cx="930" cy="470" r="11" stroke="#ff7a61" />
      <circle cx="510" cy="900" r="11" stroke="#c9f36f" />
      <circle cx="960" cy="1320" r="11" stroke="#79b7ff" />
      <circle cx="520" cy="1810" r="11" stroke="#48e0bb" />
    </svg>

    <section class="signal-section zone-paper">
      <div class="wrap">
        {/* This whole section used to run on a made-up scenario labelled
            "Illustrative operating pattern" — a hypothetical about a late
            parcel, rendered in three beautiful diagrams across a third of the
            page. It explained a concept and proved nothing, and a hiring
            manager reading "illustrative" reads "this did not happen".

            It is now one real category — withdrawals, at the fintech Ahmed
            managed support for — followed from the first ticket to the status
            mapping that was lying. The diagram survives because the case is
            genuinely four departments looking at one event and each seeing
            something that is true and useless. */}
        <header class="section-head reveal">
          <div><span class="eyebrow">01 / A — What each team saw</span><h2>Four teams looked at the same withdrawal. All four were right.</h2></div>
          <div><p>“I made a withdrawal yesterday and the money still has not arrived. Where did my money go?” — near enough the same sentence, hundreds of times. Read as a delay, it is the payments team’s problem and support can only apologise. The transfers were mostly on time.</p></div>
        </header>

        <div class="signal-map">
          <article class="signal-island signal-island--support reveal">
            <span><i class="isle__n">01</i>Support sees</span><h3>The same person, twice.</h3>
            <p>Not just the same question — the same customer coming back to ask it again, because the first answer gave them nothing they could act on. That second contact is the one nobody counts.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="signal-island signal-island--sales reveal reveal-delay-1">
            <span><i class="isle__n">02</i>Payments sees</span><h3>A transaction that completed.</h3>
            <p>Because the record says it did. The status went to Completed, the settlement looks ordinary, and one late transfer at a time is indistinguishable from a normal bank delay.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="signal-island signal-island--ops reveal reveal-delay-2">
            <span><i class="isle__n">03</i>Engineering sees</span><h3>No error at all.</h3>
            <p>The provider returned success and the system recorded success. Nothing threw, nothing alerted, nothing failed. That is exactly why it survived so long.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="signal-island signal-island--lead reveal reveal-delay-3">
            <span><i class="isle__n">04</i>Management sees</span><h3>A headcount request.</h3>
            <p>Support volume is up, so support needs people. It is the obvious read, and the only one that costs real money while changing nothing.</p>
          </article>
          <div class="signal-map__core"><strong>The record and the reality had drifted apart</strong><small>Everyone downstream trusted the record</small></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* THE CASE.

        This replaces a six-step method list — Read the raw / Find the promise /
        Ask what disappears / Write it down / Hand it over / Check honestly. Six
        verbs are a claim about how someone thinks. A case is the evidence, and
        it does the method's job without asking anyone to take it on faith.

        Every beat here is Ahmed's own account, in his own detail. Nothing is
        invented and nothing is rounded up. The one place a number appears —
        five hundred people producing nine hundred contacts — is his arithmetic
        about repeat rate, not a measurement from a specific month, and it is
        framed as the mechanism rather than a result. */}
    <section class="case-section zone-night" id="how-home">
      <div class="wrap case-shell">
        <header class="section-head reveal">
          <div><span class="eyebrow">01 / B — What I found, in the order I found it</span><h2>A company does not run on what is happening. It runs on what it has written down about what is happening.</h2></div>
          <p>Every expensive problem I have found started as a small gap between those two. Here is one category — withdrawals — followed from the first ticket down to the line that was lying. The beats are in the order I found them.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="case-list reveal">
          <Disclosure index="01" tone="night"
            title="The answer was not faster replies."
            teaser="What the customer had lost was not their money. It was any way of knowing where it was.">
            <p>All they could see was <strong>Processing</strong>. Which does not answer: is it still with you? Has it gone to the bank? Is the bank working on it? What is the difference between Processing and Completed? And if something has gone wrong, who is watching it?</p>
            <p>A person who cannot see their money and cannot see who is holding it does not experience a normal processing window. They experience a disappearance.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="02" tone="night"
            title="Repeat contact is the tell, and nobody counts it."
            teaser="Five hundred people with one unanswered question do not file five hundred tickets. They file nine hundred.">
            <p>There are two costs in a question like this, and the visible one is the smaller one. The visible cost is ticket volume. The expensive one is that the same customer comes back — once, twice — because the first answer gave them nothing they could act on.</p>
            <p>So I do not read a repeated question as <em>the customer did not read the FAQ</em>. Sometimes it means the product is not giving them enough certainty to stop asking. Which is a different problem, with a different owner, and no amount of headcount touches it.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="03" tone="night"
            title="I wrote the article. I also said the article was a patch."
            teaser="The real fix was not in the help centre. It was a status timeline inside the product.">
            <p>I wrote the content — what the stages of a withdrawal are, what each means, how long each takes. That helps. It is also a patch: you are explaining a screen instead of fixing it.</p>
            <p>The fix I proposed was in the product. Show the customer the actual timeline — <strong>Request received → Under review → Sent to payment provider → Completed</strong> — with the expected time on each stage and what happens next.</p>
            <p>Afterwards the question did not disappear. But the number of customers coming back a second time dropped clearly, and that mattered more to me than first-contact volume. <strong>First contact tells you how many people asked. Repeat contact tells you how many people you failed to answer.</strong></p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="04" tone="night"
            title="I did not write the easy article first. I wrote the expensive one."
            teaser="Ranked by repeat rate, handle time, escalation rate and how angry people were — not by how easy it was to write.">
            <p>Withdrawal questions were one of the largest contact drivers, but that is not why I started there. I started there because those tickets also had the highest repeat rate, the longest handle time, the highest escalation rate and the angriest customers in the queue. Fixing that one question would not only reduce volume — it would take pressure off the team and stop cases reaching supervisors.</p>
            <p>And I wrote it backwards from the usual FAQ. Not a definition first, but the question actually in the customer’s head: <em>“Withdrawal late? Before you worry — find out which stage your request is at.”</em></p>
            <p>Instead of <em>“Completed means the transaction was successfully processed by the payment provider”</em>, it said: <strong>Completed means we have finished our side. Your bank may still need extra time before the amount shows in your account.</strong></p>
            <p>Then the part most FAQs leave out entirely — <strong>when should you contact us?</strong> An article that explains a status but never tells a person what to do has not finished its job. So it named the cases: if the normal window has not passed, wait. If it has, send the transaction ID. If it says Completed and the money is not there, check your statement, not your notifications.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="05" tone="night"
            title="“You are a scam company and I will expose you everywhere.”"
            teaser="The money never reached us. Telling him that would have been true, and useless.">
            <p>That was the first message. The standard reply — <em>“We apologise for the inconvenience, please send the transaction ID”</em> — would have made it worse. It answers the procedure and ignores the person, and he would have heard a template.</p>
            <p>What I sent instead: <em>“I understand that what you can see right now is that the amount left your account and the service did not happen — and it makes sense that it feels like your money is gone. Let me check the actual transaction rather than give you a general answer. Send me the last four digits of the payment method and roughly when it happened, and I will tell you whether the amount was really taken or whether it is a temporary hold from your bank, and what happens next.”</em></p>
            <p>I did not tell him he was wrong and I did not start by defending the company. The first thing to give back to someone in that state is not an apology — it is the sense that somebody has understood the problem and owns it.</p>
            <p>It was an <strong>authorisation hold</strong>. The transaction had failed before completing; the money never reached us at all. The bank had simply reserved it.</p>
            <p>The useless version of that answer is <em>“that is your bank’s problem, call your bank.”</em> What I sent was: the amount did not reach us, here is the transaction reference and its status so you do not have to explain from zero if you call them, this normally releases automatically within the bank’s window — and if it has not come back by that date, reply here and I will escalate it to the payments team.</p>
            <p>He came back two days later to confirm it had returned, and apologised for how he had opened. The apology is not the win. The win is moving someone from <em>my money has vanished and nobody is responsible</em> to: this is what happened, this person is holding it, this is when it resolves, and this is what happens if it does not.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="06" tone="night"
            title="Then I got the team. The first thing I changed was not the scripts."
            teaser="It was the categories — because every decision after that is made on top of them.">
            <p>Not headcount, not SLAs, not macros. Ticket taxonomy and problem ownership.</p>
            <p>What I inherited was: Payment Issue. Technical Issue. Account Issue. Other. Categories that make a report look organised and teach you nothing. <strong>Payment Issue</strong> contained late withdrawals, deposits not showing, declined transactions, duplicate charges, temporary bank holds, wrong beneficiary details, and a problem with one specific provider. In the report, all of that was one bar — so we could not tell whether the problem was the product, the bank, the provider or our own instructions.</p>
            <p>I rebuilt it so every ticket carried: the reason for contact, the actual cause after investigation, the product or feature affected, the stage of the customer journey, the department that owns the origin, and whether the contact was preventable at all.</p>
            <p><strong>Reason for contact is not the same thing as cause, and the difference is where the money is.</strong> A customer writes in because a withdrawal is late. Investigation shows their bank details were incomplete. Log it as “late withdrawal” and you go and put pressure on the payments team — while the real problem is sitting in a data-entry screen.</p>
            <p>I started with categories because every decision downstream stands on them. If the data says thirty per cent payment problems but not which kind, I cannot tell you whether to hire agents, fix a bug, change a sentence in the product or renegotiate with a provider. I would just be guessing with a chart open.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="07" tone="night"
            title="Every number was green. The customer was not."
            teaser="First response time was excellent because agents were replying with nothing.">
            <p>Metrics said the team was performing and the experience said otherwise. Tickets resolved was high, the SLA was green, and then I read what the replies actually said. <em>“We have received your request and it is under review.”</em> Sent fast, SLA met, zero information given.</p>
            <p>Some tickets were closed early to bring the backlog down. The customer would reply and the ticket reopened. Visible backlog low; reopen rate and repeat contact rate both high.</p>
            <p>And the macros were not unified, so the same problem got three different answers from three agents. One said two to three days. One said five. One told the customer to contact their bank immediately. <strong>A customer who writes in twice and gets two different answers has not received two answers. They have received evidence that nobody knows.</strong></p>
            <p>So I stopped measuring adherence and started reviewing the decision: did the agent reach the correct information, did they explain it in a way this customer could use, did they name the next step, and was the cause recorded so it stops happening? An agent can be perfectly polite, hit every required phrase, and still send someone in the wrong direction and leave the problem with no owner.</p>
            <p>And I separated <strong>ticket resolution</strong> from <strong>problem resolution</strong>. An agent can close a ticket while the problem stays exactly where it is and produces a hundred more tomorrow. My job was not to confirm tickets were closed. It was to know why they opened.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="08" tone="night"
            title="And then: “Completed” did not mean completed."
            teaser="We were telling customers their money had arrived. It had not.">
            <p>A small number of withdrawals were showing <strong>Completed</strong>, and some of those customers were telling us the money had not arrived. One at a time, each case is explainable as an ordinary bank delay. That is exactly why it survived. It only becomes visible if you refuse to look at them one at a time.</p>
            <p>Grouped, there was a pattern: all inside one time window, all on the same payment provider, and all with the status flipping to Completed suspiciously soon after the request was sent.</p>
            <p>So I did not escalate them one at a time. I wrote one incident summary — customers affected, total amounts, timing of each transaction, our status, the provider’s status, expected behaviour against actual. Then Payments Operations, to check the settlement files. Then Engineering, for the webhook and the status mapping. Then Finance, to confirm whether the money had actually left the settlement account.</p>
            <p>The cause: our system was treating the provider’s first response as final success. That response means <em>accepted for processing</em>. It does not mean the transfer happened. We had collapsed two different things into one word — <strong>accepted for processing is not successfully settled</strong>. A tiny percentage of transactions, and the most dangerous thing in the queue, because we were telling people their money had arrived while it was still in flight.</p>
            <p>Three fixes: the status only becomes Completed after final settlement confirmation; a real intermediate state — <strong>Sent to provider</strong> — so the truth has somewhere to live; and every affected transaction pulled and reviewed proactively rather than waiting for each customer to notice.</p>
            <p>The customers did not get <em>“we are experiencing a technical delay.”</em> They got: <em>“We reviewed your withdrawal and found the status showed as completed before the final confirmation arrived from the payment provider. The transaction is not lost — it is still processing, and we are tracking it as a priority. Your next update will come before [date], even if nothing has changed.”</em></p>
            <p><strong>Even if nothing has changed.</strong> That clause is the whole thing. The biggest mistake in escalation management is contacting the customer only when you have a solution. People can tolerate a delay. They cannot tolerate silence and not knowing whether anyone is holding it.</p>
            <p>And we did not close the bug and move on. We added a monitoring alert for when the share of transactions sitting in the intermediate state crossed a threshold, and a playbook for when support converts a cluster of tickets into an incident instead of working them individually.</p>
          </Disclosure>

          <Disclosure index="09" tone="night"
            title="This is one category, in one company. The shape does not change."
            teaser="Read it back. Every layer is the same failure wearing different clothes.">
            <p>A status that reported a state instead of a truth. An article that explained a definition instead of a decision. A word — Completed — that meant one thing to us and another to the customer. A category that replaced the fact it was supposed to describe. A metric that was satisfied while the customer was not. A backlog that fell while the work did not. A status mapping that was, in plain terms, wrong.</p>
            <p>Every one of those is a gap between what was happening and what the company had written down about what was happening.</p>
            <p><strong>And the gap does not grow in a straight line as a company grows. It compounds</strong> — because everything downstream is decided on the record rather than the reality. A wrong status generates a contact. A wrong category generates a wrong report. A wrong report generates a headcount decision. And now you are paying salaries to answer a question that should not exist, and the report says support is busy. Which it is.</p>
            <p>That is the real cost in operations. Not one big failure — a thousand small drifts, each individually defensible, all being multiplied by growth.</p>
            <p>Which is why I do not think support is a department that answers questions. <strong>It is the only place in the building where you can see the difference between what a company believes about itself and what is actually true.</strong></p>
          </Disclosure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="impact-section zone-paper">
      <div class="wrap">
        <header class="section-head reveal">
          <div><span class="eyebrow">01 / C — What was left behind</span><h2>None of it was a chatbot, more agents, or a tracking product.</h2></div>
          <p>The test I hold myself to is not whether the queue went quiet. A queue goes quiet when the work moves somewhere nobody is measuring. The test is whether the reason to ask was removed, and whether the thing that caused it can come back without anyone noticing.</p>
        </header>

        {/* The outcome of a real case, so it names what it cannot claim. Ahmed
            has no exported dashboard and will not invent one, so the honest
            statement is which direction moved and which number he refused to
            chase — not a percentage nobody can source. */}
        <div class="impact-system">
          <article class="impact-petal impact-petal--support reveal"><span><i class="isle__n">01</i>The customer</span><h3>A timeline instead of a word.</h3><p>Four stages the customer can watch, each with the time it should take. Not a faster answer — no reason to ask for one.</p></article>
          <article class="impact-petal impact-petal--sales reveal reveal-delay-1"><span><i class="isle__n">02</i>The data</span><h3>Cause recorded apart from complaint.</h3><p>Every ticket now carries what the customer said and what was actually wrong. Those two were one field before, and that single missing distinction had been aiming every decision at the wrong department.</p></article>
          <article class="impact-petal impact-petal--ops reveal reveal-delay-2"><span><i class="isle__n">03</i>The system</span><h3>A status that stopped lying.</h3><p>Completed only after settlement confirms, a real intermediate state so the truth has somewhere to live, and a monitoring alert so it cannot drift back quietly.</p></article>
          <article class="impact-petal impact-petal--lead reveal reveal-delay-3"><span><i class="isle__n">04</i>The team</span><h3>Quality became the decision, not the script.</h3><p>Thirteen people, reviewed on whether the customer could act on the answer rather than whether the phrasing was approved. An agent can hit every required word and still leave a problem with no owner.</p></article>
          <div class="impact-core"><span>Measured on</span><strong>Repeat contact, not first response</strong></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
    </div>
  </details>

  {/* SECOND CASE — deliberately NOT built like the first one.

      The withdrawal case is a descent: one shaft, dug down layer by layer, so
      it is told as a ladder of numbered beats. This one is a collision. Ahmed
      asked for documents instead of opinions, and the documents disagreed with
      each other. There is no sequence to walk down — the whole argument is
      seeing them laid side by side.

      So: exhibits, on paper, nothing collapsed. Repeating the disclosure device
      here would have made the second case feel like a reprise of the first
      rather than a different kind of work.

      His account, in his detail. He wrote it in the first person plural; he has
      confirmed it was his own engagement and that the "we" was modesty, so it
      reads as "I" like the rest of the page. */}

  <details class="case" id="dossier" data-case>
    <summary class="case__head">
      <span class="case__n">Case 02</span>
      <span class="case__titles">
        <span class="case__t">A company telling its customer five different things.</span>
        <span class="case__ctx">Mid-size e-commerce · consulting engagement · sector described, not named</span>
      </span>
      <span class="case__open">Read the case</span>
      <span class="case__chev" aria-hidden="true"><svg viewBox="0 0 16 10" width="16" height="10"><path d="M1 1l7 7 7-7" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" /></svg></span>
    </summary>
    <div class="case__body">
  <section class="dossier-section zone-paper">
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="section-head reveal">
        <div><span class="eyebrow">02 / A — The documents, side by side</span><h2>Every document made sense. Read side by side, they told five different stories.</h2></div>
        <div>
          <p>The withdrawal case was one status lying inside one system. This is the same failure with the volume turned up — a mid-size e-commerce business where every department was right, every number was green, and the same company was promising its customer five different things.</p>
          <p class="dossier-sting">They hired me to fix customer service. Customer service was the only part that was not broken.</p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="dossier-brief reveal">
        <span class="proof-label">The brief</span>
        <blockquote>“We need to improve customer service. Better scripts, and a faster response time.”</blockquote>
        <p>The easiest brief I have ever been given, and the one thing I did not do. From the first meeting it was obvious that support was not the problem — support was just where all the problems finished.</p>
        <p>So I asked for documents instead of opinions: the returns policy, the ad copy, sales and support transcripts, the order and cancellation reports, the inventory sheet, the fulfilment SOP, the carrier’s own reports, the negative reviews, every team’s KPIs, the org chart. Including the files I was told had nothing to do with customer service.</p>
        <p><strong>Read one at a time, every single one of them was reasonable. That is exactly why nobody had found it.</strong></p>
      </div>

      <article class="exhibit exhibit--wide reveal">
        <span class="exhibit__tag">Exhibit A</span>
        <h3>The same promise, five ways.</h3>
        <dl class="exhibit__rows">
          <div><dt>The advert</dt><dd>“Delivered in 48 hours.”</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Sales, on the phone</dt><dd>“Usually two or three days.”</dd></div>
          <div><dt>The shipping policy</dt><dd>“Three to seven business days.”</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Support’s internal rule</dt><dd>An order is not late until day five.</dd></div>
          <div><dt>The carrier</dt><dd>Counts from the moment they collect it. Not from the moment you ordered.</dd></div>
        </dl>
        <ol class="clock">
          <li><span>Sat</span>The customer orders — and starts counting.</li>
          <li><span>Mon</span>The warehouse picks and packs.</li>
          <li><span>Tue</span>The carrier collects — and starts counting.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="exhibit__note">Every one of those statements is true from inside the department that made it. By Monday the customer is forty-eight hours in and the only clock that counts has not started. When they write in asking where their order is, that arrives as a support failure — and support cannot repair a promise made in an advert, reinterpreted by sales, and measured by a third department.</p>
      </article>

      <div class="exhibit-pair">
        <article class="exhibit reveal">
          <span class="exhibit__tag">Exhibit B</span>
          <h3>The cancellation that was not one.</h3>
          <dl class="exhibit__rows">
            <div><dt>What the report said</dt><dd>“Customer changed their mind.”</dd></div>
            <div><dt>What the conversation said</dt><dd>We called two days later to say the colour was out of stock and offered a substitute. They said no.</dd></div>
          </dl>
          <p class="exhibit__note">The code is not false — they did refuse. It is just not the cause. The cause is that we sold something we did not have: the inventory sheet was updated by hand, and the website, the sales team and the warehouse were never looking at the same number at the same moment. Two reps can confirm the last two units at once. Marketing books a conversion, sales books a confirmed order, and support receives the customer.</p>
          <p class="exhibit__note"><strong>A cause you have miscoded is a cause you will never fix.</strong> Management was reading a report telling it that it had a lot of unserious customers.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="exhibit exhibit--dark reveal reveal-delay-1">
          <span class="exhibit__tag">Exhibit C</span>
          <h3>“Confirmed.” One word, three meanings.</h3>
          <dl class="exhibit__rows">
            <div><dt>To sales it meant</dt><dd>the customer said yes.</dd></div>
            <div><dt>To the warehouse</dt><dd>we checked, and the stock is real.</dd></div>
            <div><dt>To management</dt><dd>ready to enter fulfilment.</dd></div>
          </dl>
          <p class="exhibit__note">The smallest document in the pile — a plain order-tracking sheet — and the one that broke the case open. An order could sit in management’s report as confirmed while nobody had looked in the warehouse. Support could tell a customer their order was confirmed and discover the next day that the product did not exist.</p>
          <p class="exhibit__note"><strong>The company did not have a definition of the truth. It had one per department, and was reading them as if they were the same one.</strong></p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict reveal">
        <h3>Marketing owned the advert. Sales owned the confirmation. The warehouse owned the pick. The carrier owned the van. Support owned the apology. <em>Nobody owned the promise.</em></h3>
        <div class="verdict__grid">
          <p>Every team was hitting its number, and hitting it honestly. Marketing was measured on orders, so the promises got bolder. Sales on confirmations, so they closed fast and committed to dates operations had never seen. The warehouse on orders shipped, so the order left — not necessarily correct. Support on speed and closures, so a generic update went out, the conversation closed, and the cause stayed exactly where it was.</p>
          <p>Almost every problem lived in the distance between two departments, which is the one place no KPI was pointed at. They were managing departments. Nobody was managing a journey.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rebuild reveal">
        <Disclosure
          index="→"
          title="What I rebuilt, and why it did not start with training"
          teaser="Training someone on a system that is not clear only teaches them to explain the chaos more politely."
          tone="paper"
        >
          <p>I rebuilt the order journey into stages that admit exactly one reading — received, awaiting stock check, stock confirmed, confirmed with the customer, preparing, ready for the carrier, collected, out for delivery, delivered, failed, return requested, return under review, returned, refunded. Every stage got five things: a definition, the department that owns it, how long it is normal to sit there, the next action, and who moves when it overruns.</p>
          <p>Complaints stopped being recorded as outcomes and started carrying three fields: what the customer said, what was actually wrong, and which stage produced it. <em>Late delivery / warehouse backlog / fulfilment</em> is a completely different instruction to a business than <em>late delivery</em>. The reports changed shape overnight — a share of the cancellations turned out to be our own errors, and part of the delay the carrier was being blamed for had happened before the carrier ever touched the parcel.</p>
          <p>Escalations stopped being “can someone look at this order?” in a group chat and started arriving as a case ready for a decision: order number, expected behaviour, what actually happened, current stage, the department that must act, the specific action, the priority, and when the update is due. Support stopped throwing problems over a wall, and the other side stopped receiving them without an owner or a deadline.</p>
          <p>And any advert carrying an operational promise went past operations before it ran — not to make marketing timid, but to make the promise both strong and survivable. <strong>A successful advert is not the one that brings the most orders. It is the one that brings orders you can keep your promise on.</strong></p>
          <p>I also stopped letting the ticket count define the problem. Most customers with a problem never write in: they cancel without explaining, or receive it late and quietly never order again, or refuse the substitute and disappear, or leave a review instead of a message. So the signal came from cancellations after confirmation, delivery failures, customers who did not come back, orders sitting longer than normal at a stage, products substituted most often, and which promise carried the highest complaint rate. The company started seeing the problems that had been happening in silence.</p>
        </Disclosure>
      </div>

      <p class="dossier-close reveal">They came convinced they had a customer service problem. If I had written them better scripts, the apologies would have been more beautiful and the problems identical — the agent apologising more gracefully for an order confirmed against stock that never existed, explaining more politely why a shipment was late, calming a customer the company had given three different dates. <strong>Consulting is not about helping a company apologise better. It is about finding out why it has to apologise at all.</strong></p>
    </div>
  </section>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="case" id="evidence" data-case>
    <summary class="case__head">
      <span class="case__n">Case 03</span>
      <span class="case__titles">
        <span class="case__t">The one where the decision was mine.</span>
        <span class="case__ctx">Formula4You · live platform · founder</span>
      </span>
      <span class="case__open">Read the case</span>
      <span class="case__chev" aria-hidden="true"><svg viewBox="0 0 16 10" width="16" height="10"><path d="M1 1l7 7 7-7" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" /></svg></span>
    </summary>
    <div class="case__body">
  <section class="proof-section zone-raised">
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="section-head reveal">
        <div><span class="eyebrow">03 / A — The gap, and three decisions</span><h2>The gap was not a missing product. It was a missing place.</h2></div>
        <p>Both of those cases were other people’s companies, and a consultant can always leave. This is the one where the decision was mine, there was nobody above me to sign it off, and I am the person who answers for it.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="gap-grid">
        <figure class="gap-shot reveal">
          <Image src={formulaHome} alt="The live Formula4You specialist fragrance-commerce platform" widths={[520, 760, 1040]} sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 46vw" />
          <figcaption>The live platform</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <div class="gap-read reveal reveal-delay-1">
          <p>Egypt’s fragrance market was never short of people. Suppliers, manufacturers, sellers and buyers were all already there — and all of them were working through tools built for selling anything at all.</p>
          <p>A general storefront does not know how a fragrance gets chosen, what makes a supplier believable, or which facts a buyer needs before they will trust a bottle they cannot smell. So the market was not fragmented because it was small. It was fragmented because nothing had been built for the way it actually works.</p>
          <p><strong>The gap was not a product nobody was selling. It was a market with no place built for it.</strong></p>
          <p>I mapped the participants, reviewed what already existed, and put that against what I already knew from being inside the category. Then I made three decisions, and the whole thing rests on them.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ol class="calls">
        <li class="call reveal">
          <span class="call__n">01</span>
          <h3>Specialist, not general.</h3>
          <p>A general online store competes with everyone alive on price and delivery — and both of those are won by whoever has the most money to lose. A platform built for one category competes on relevance instead. Relevance is the only advantage that compounds rather than being outspent.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="call reveal reveal-delay-1">
          <span class="call__n">02</span>
          <h3>Supply before demand.</h3>
          <p>The acquisition plan was ready. I did not run it. The tempting order is to buy attention and hope supply catches up, because a traffic chart is a thing you can show people. I went credible suppliers first, then data structure, then inventory worth arriving for — and customers last. Every step before that looked slower and less impressive. <strong>An empty marketplace does not fail quietly: it teaches the first wave that you have nothing, and they do not come back to check.</strong></p>
        </li>
        <li class="call reveal reveal-delay-2">
          <span class="call__n">03</span>
          <h3>Rules before features.</h3>
          <p>Who may list. What happens when a listing is wrong. What a buyer is owed and who fixes it. Renewals, expired accounts, review controls, what an admin can and cannot override. None of it demos well and all of it decides whether the place is still trustworthy in year two — operating rules are not documentation, they are what a business does when something breaks at 2am and nobody is watching.</p>
        </li>
      </ol>

      {/* The three decisions are the strategy; these are what it produced. Real
          platform counts, not estimates — the one figure I could not stand
          behind stays out of the case, which is what makes these believable. */}
      <div class="gap-nums reveal">
        <p class="gap-nums__intro">I ran it supply-first and held the acquisition spend until the platform was worth arriving for. The first month of execution:</p>
        <div class="gap-nums__grid">
          <div class="gap-num"><span class="gap-num__n">42</span><span class="gap-num__l">suppliers onboarded</span></div>
          <div class="gap-num"><span class="gap-num__n">55</span><span class="gap-num__l">merchant stores activated</span></div>
          <div class="gap-num"><span class="gap-num__n">~400</span><span class="gap-num__l">orders in the first month</span></div>
          <div class="gap-num"><span class="gap-num__n">7.3</span><span class="gap-num__l">orders per merchant</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="gap-close reveal">
        <p class="formula-proof__role">Founder — Business Growth, Customer Experience &amp; Platform Operations</p>
        <div class="cluster">
          <a class="btn btn--primary" href={withBase('/work/formula4you')}>Read the full case</a>
          <a class="btn" href={external.formula4you} rel="noopener">Visit the live platform ↗</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
    </div>
  </details>

  {/* This was five rows of Title Case Capability Names — "Business Performance
      Interpretation", "AI-Aware Workflow Decisions" — each ending on the same
      "I am not an X" beat. Nobody talks like that, and I had just deleted the
      capability essays for the identical crime while leaving their twin
      standing. The boundary earns its place; the parade did not. */}
  <section class="lenses-section zone-paper" id="boundary">
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="section-head reveal">
        <div><span class="eyebrow">Where I stop</span><h2>I decide what needs to exist and why. Building it is a different craft, and I work with the people who have it.</h2></div>
        <p>The status mapping was an engineer’s. The timeline screen was a designer’s. Formula4You is a developer’s. My part was deciding what needed to exist and why, writing it down clearly enough that they did not have to guess — and saying out loud when the answer was that nothing should be built at all.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="lens-list">
        <article class="lens-row reveal">
          <span>01</span><h3>Where a journey leaks</h3>
          <p>I can tell you which sentence is costing you the order and roughly what it costs. I write the requirement; a designer builds the screen.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="lens-row reveal">
          <span>02</span><h3>Reading the numbers</h3>
          <p>Start from the business question, not the dashboard: pick the indicator that actually answers it, then read what the pattern means. Building the pipeline is an engineer’s job, and I leave it there.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="lens-row reveal">
          <span>03</span><h3>Deciding what gets built</h3>
          <p>The problem, the need, the acceptance logic, and whether building is warranted at all. Architecture belongs to engineers. A manager who pretends otherwise is how a team ends up building the same thing twice.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="lens-row reveal">
          <span>04</span><h3>Whether AI helps</h3>
          <p>Usually it would add cost without touching the cause — which is a less popular answer than it should be. Knowing when not to build a thing is most of what I am for.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="build-rule reveal">
        <span>Simplify</span><i>→</i><span>Automate</span><i>→</i><span>Build</span>
        <p>Building is the last option, not the first reaction. A clearer sentence, one fewer field, or a named owner will often outperform a feature — and all three are cheaper to undo.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


  {/* The employer/business fork is gone. Asking a visitor to classify
      themselves before they have read anything was a decision they had no
      basis to make — and it split one evidence base into two weaker doors.
      One page, one close. */}
  <section class="routes-section zone-paper" id="talk">
    <div class="wrap">
      <header class="section-head reveal">
        <div><span class="eyebrow">If any of this landed</span><h2>Tell me what is not working. I will tell you where it actually lives.</h2></div>
        <div>
          <p>Whether you are hiring or you run the business, the first reply is the same: whether the problem fits what I do, and what evidence I would need to answer it properly. If it is not a fit, I will say so.</p>
          {/* Free, and said without the halo. "I am doing you a favour" is the
              fastest way to make someone not ask — and it would not be true.
              An hour inside a real problem is worth more to him than a month of
              reading about one, which is a reason to believe the offer rather
              than a reason to be grateful for it. */}
          <p class="close-free"><strong>The first conversation is free, and it is not a favour.</strong> An hour inside a real problem teaches me more than a month of reading about one — so I get as much out of it as you do. That is the whole arrangement.</p>
        </div>
      </header>

      {/* "Download the CV" used to sit here as a third action, and it was the
          one thing on the page arguing the opposite of everything else. The
